  "local_port": 45578,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I get rid of little bumps on my face?",
  "response": "Getting rid of little bumps on your face depends on their cause. These bumps can include acne, closed comedones, milia, keratosis pilaris, or irritation. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you address them:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Identify the Type of Bumps**  \n   - **Acne**: Red, inflamed, or pus-filled bumps.  \n   - **Closed Comedones (Whiteheads)**: Small, flesh-colored bumps.  \n   - **Milia**: Hard, white bumps under the skin.  \n   - **Keratosis Pilaris**: Rough, chicken-skin-like texture.  \n   - **Irritation or Allergic Reaction**: Red, itchy, or painful bumps.\n\nIf you\u2019re unsure, consult a dermatologist for a proper diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Gentle Cleansing**  \n   - Use a **gentle, non-comedogenic cleanser** twice daily to remove dirt, oil, and impurities.  \n   - Avoid harsh scrubs or products with alcohol, which can irritate the skin.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Exfoliation**  \n   - Use a **chemical exfoliant** (like salicylic acid, glycolic acid, or lactic acid) 2\u20133 times a week to unclog pores and remove dead skin cells.  \n   - Avoid physical scrubs if your skin is sensitive.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Moisturize**  \n   - Use a lightweight, non-comedogenic moisturizer to keep your skin hydrated.  \n   - Look for ingredients like hyaluronic acid, ceramides, or niacinamide.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Targeted Treatments**  \n   - **Acne**: Use benzoyl peroxide, salicylic acid, or retinoids.  \n   - **Closed Comedones**: Retinoids (e.g., adapalene) or AHAs/BHAs.  \n   - **Milia**: Professional extraction by a dermatologist.  \n   - **Keratosis Pilaris**: Urea or lactic acid creams.  \n   - **Irritation**: Avoid harsh products and use soothing ingredients like aloe vera or colloidal oatmeal.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Avoid Irritants**  \n   - Stop using heavy makeup or skincare products that clog pores.  \n   - Patch-test new products to prevent allergic reactions.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Sun Protection**  \n   - Wear a broad-spectrum SPF 30+ daily to prevent sun damage, which can worsen bumps.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Diet and Lifestyle**  \n   - Maintain a healthy diet, stay hydrated, and manage stress.  \n   - Avoid touching your face with dirty hands.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Consult a Dermatologist**  \n   If the bumps persist or worsen, see a dermatologist for prescription treatments (e.g., retinoids, antibiotics, or procedures like extractions).\n\n---\n\n### Example Routine:  \n**AM**:  \n1. Gentle cleanser  \n2. Salicylic acid toner (if needed)  \n3. Lightweight moisturizer  \n4. SPF 30+  \n\n**PM**:  \n1. Gentle cleanser  \n2. Retinoid or treatment serum  \n3. Moisturizer  \n\n---\n\nConsistency is key, and results may take a few weeks. Always patch-test new products and avoid over-treating your skin to prevent irritation.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
